                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1/935: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hull</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-06-11T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 11, 1933—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>20. Your 19, June 11, 6 p.m. Learning that Conference Committee on Industrial
                    Control bill had amended subsection (<hi rend="italic">e</hi>) of Title I making
                    it mandatory, I discussed your telegram with the President this afternoon,
                        Livesey<note n="46" xml:id="d455fn46">Frederick Livesey, Assistant Economic
                        Adviser, Department of State.</note> aiding. The President telephoned
                    Senator Harrison,<note n="47" xml:id="d455fn47">Pat Harrison, Chairman of the
                        Senate Finance Committee.</note> who agreed immediately to introduce a joint
                    resolution correcting the Conference Report.</p>
                <p>The President sees absolutely no obstacle to the introduction of the tariff truce
                    resolution. He assumes that your draft will safeguard our position against
                    dumping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
